{"id": "EUVD-2025-201638", "enisaUuid": "e5394ec0-57e8-3ba0-9025-77e10157f1fe", "description": "In the Linux kernel, the following vulnerability has been resolved:\n\nexfat: validate cluster allocation bits of the allocation bitmap\n\nsyzbot created an exfat image with cluster bits not set for the allocation\nbitmap. exfat-fs reads and uses the allocation bitmap without checking\nthis. The problem is that if the start cluster of the allocation bitmap\nis 6, cluster 6 can be allocated when creating a directory with mkdir.\nexfat zeros out this cluster in exfat_mkdir, which can delete existing\nentries. This can reallocate the allocated entries. In addition,\nthe allocation bitmap is also zeroed out, so cluster 6 can be reallocated.\nThis patch adds exfat_test_bitmap_range to validate that clusters used for\nthe allocation bitmap are correctly marked as in-use.", "datePublished": "2025-12-08T00:46:32", "dateUpdated": "2025-12-20T08:51:58", "baseScore": 0.0, "references": ["https://git.kernel.org/stable/c/6bc58b4c53795ab5fe00648344aa7d9d61175f90", "https://git.kernel.org/stable/c/13c1d24803d5b0446b3f6f0fdd67e07ac1fdc7bf", "https://git.kernel.org/stable/c/79c1587b6cda74deb0c86fc7ba194b92958c793c", "https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2025-40307"], "aliases": ["CVE-2025-40307"], "assigner": "Linux", "epss": 0.02, "enisaIdProduct": [{"id": "215a14b0-b409-35d5-88d0-07a8872322a6", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "patch: 6.18"}, {"id": "2ab8382e-0e74-3695-9a44-2f364220410f", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "1acf1a564b6034b5af1e7fb23cb98cb3bb4f6003 <79c1587b6cda74deb0c86fc7ba194b92958c793c"}, {"id": "2cbea57c-8f6e-3492-aaae-0c0d880b26cd", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "5.7"}, {"id": "428c69f5-3980-35d2-b809-dd63aba8c65d", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "patch: 6.12.58"}, {"id": "4888c63f-254f-371c-a127-43b89adb203f", "product": {"name": "Linux"}, "product_version": "1acf1a564b6034b5af1e7fb23cb98cb3bb4f600